14.body: Each value has a variable called its owner There can only be one owner at a time When the owner goes out of scope, the value is dropped Ownership applies to data types of non-fixed size stored on the heap eg. String as opposed to string literals: let mut s = String::from("hello"); s.push_str(", world!"); // push_str() appends a literal to a String println!("{}", s); // This will print `hello, world!`
14.title: Ownership

15.body: let s1 = String::from("hello"); let s2 = s1; Both s1 and s2 are pointers on the stack to data on the heap. Once a variable goes out of scope, Rust calls the drop function to clean up the heap memory for that variable. Assigning s1 to s2 invalidates the reference s1. s1 is moved into s2. Invalidating the first variable prevents the double free error.

32.title: Enumerations

33.body:
Rust does not have null, but has Option type, which can be something or nothing. It is defined by the standard library as follows: enum Option<T> { Some(T), None,
} Option<T>, Some and None are included in the prelude and do not need to be brought into scope, and therefore do not require the Option:: prefix. let some_number = Some(5); let some_string = Some("a string"); let absent_number: Option<i32> = None; If a variable is initialized with None a type needs to be specified in the generic. Does not compile: let x: i8 = 5; let y: Option<i8> = Some(5); let sum = x + y; *Option<T> must be converted to T before performing T operations with it. (see next section)
33.title: Option Enum

34.title: match Control Flow Operator

35.body: let some_u8_value = Some(0u8); match some_u8_value { Some(3) => println!("three"), _ => (), } equivalent to: if let Some(3) = some_u8_value { println!("three"); } if let is more concise than match but does not provide exhaustive checking Combining if let with else if let Some(3) = some_u8_value { println!("three"); } else { println!("not three"); }

36.body: Packages: A Cargo feature that lets you build, test, and share crates Crates: A tree of modules that produces a library or executable Modules and use: Let you control the organization, scope, and privacy of paths Paths: A way of naming an item, such as a struct, function, or module
36.title: Packages, Crates and Modules

37.body: Crates are binary packages or library packages. Binary packages are created with cargo new and have src/main.rs as the crate root. Library crates are created with cargo new --lib and have src/lib.rs as the crate root.
